<section id="fb1">
	<p align="left">New Zealanders</p><p align="left">We don't know if the people surveyed attended cultural events or not.</p>
</section>
<section id="fb2">
	<p align="left">The quality of the events is not referred to in the chart. A better phrase would be <font color="#0000ff">...regarding cultural matters.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb3">
	<p align="left">agree</p><p align="left">For three of the five statements, the vast majority agree or agree strongly.</p>
</section>
<section id="fb4">
	<p align="left">New Zealanders</p><p align="left">74 per cent refers to New Zealanders.</p>
</section>
<section id="fb5">
	<p align="left">Similarly...</p>
</section>
<section id="fb6">
	<p align="left">What follows this linking phrase contrasts or contradicts the point which is made before. So it could be <font color="#0000ff">... However,</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb7">
	<p align="left">We use 'as...as' to compare things. 'Such as' introduces examples. <font color="#0000ff"></font></p><p align="left"><font color="#0000ff">...is not <b>so</b>&#32;unanimous...</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb8">
	<p align="left">'Than' follows as comparative adjective, 'bigger than' for example, but not comparatives with 'as'. <font color="#0000ff"></font></p><p align="left"><font color="#0000ff">...on some issues <b>as</b>&#32;it is on others.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb9">
	<p align="left">After a comparative adjective we use 'than', not 'as'.</p>
</section>
<section id="fb10">
	<p align="left">...those who think sport is more important...</p>
</section>
<section id="fb11">
	<p align="left">The point that follows this linking phrase is another example of what New Zealanders disagree about.</p><p align="left"><font color="#0000ff">Likewise, ...</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb12">
	<p align="left">2 in 5</p>
</section>
